Fitting advanced N-mixture models

To run this analysis, we recommend that you take a larger sample size, e.g., 20 sites per site covariate used. If there is too many covariates in the model (relative to sample size), the model will not estimate the parameters correctly. You might get NAs as a result. If you do not have a sufficient sample size to incorporate the model extensions, we recommend leaving this one out to avoid making an incorrect analysis. For this analysis, we will be using a much larger data set named hornbill2.csv, that comprise of 92 independent sites.

#load data set
hornbill2 <- read.csv("hornbill2.csv", comment = "#", header = TRUE)
#load R package
install.packages("unmarked")
library(unmarked)
#re-organise input data
umf <- unmarkedFramePCount(
    y = hornbill2[, c("occ1", "occ2", "occ3")],                             
    siteCovs = data.frame(elevation = hornbill2$elevation, forest = hornbill2$forest),  
    obsCovs = list(day = hornbill2[, c("day1", "day2", "day3")],                
                   duration = hornbill2[, c("dur1", "dur2", "dur3")]))
summary(umf)

Fitting N-mixture models with covariate effects

So far, you have a simple model that does not include covariate effects. If you have many sampling sites, you can try fitting N-mixture models that include covariate effects. In some situations, perhaps habitat conditions and sampling efforts might explain the variation in abundance and detection much better than simply assuming them to be constant. One way to find out is to create a set of models containing a different combination of your covariates.

Perhaps site conditions and sampling efforts might explain the variation in detection and abundance better than simply assuming them to be constant. This example generates 13 more models using every possible combination of site and observation covariates. This will take some time to run, and hence we recommend choosing carefully candidate model sets based on your knowledge of the species/system instead of this approach.

So here are the models written in the unmarked notation.

#constant detection and abundance 
m1 <- pcount(~1 ~1, K = 100, data = umf)

#variations in detection (constant abundance)
m2 <- pcount(~day ~1, K = 100, data = umf)
m3 <- pcount(~duration ~1, K = 100, data = umf)
m4 <- pcount(~day+duration ~1, K = 100, data = umf)

#variations in abundance (constant detection)
m5 <- pcount(~1 ~elevation, K = 100, data = umf)
m6 <- pcount(~1 ~elevation, K = 100, data = umf)
m7 <- pcount(~1 ~elevation+forest, K = 100, data = umf)

#variations in both detection and abundance
m8 <- pcount(~day ~elevation, K = 100, data = umf)
m9 <- pcount(~duration ~elevation, K = 100, data = umf)
m10 <- pcount(~day ~forest, K = 100, data = umf)
m11 <- pcount(~day ~forest, K = 100, data = umf)
m12 <- pcount(~day+duration ~elevation, K = 100, data = umf)
m13 <- pcount(~day+duration ~forest, K = 100, data = umf)
m14 <- pcount(~day+duration ~elevation+forest, K = 100, data = umf)


Choosing best model

So you could fit any model, but in practice, you do not usually know what the truth is in this case. You have a different hypothesis about what you think might drive abundance and what might variation in detection. If you sit down and think of all the ways things in nature could vary, you would potentially end up with many competing models.

Once you have created several possible models, you can use the Akaike Information Criterion (AIC) to compare them. In plain words, AIC is a single number score that is used to determine which of the models is most likely to be the best model for a given data. It estimates models relatively, meaning that AIC scores are only useful in comparison with other AIC scores for the same data. A lower AIC score is better and will be the better-fit model.

You can run the aictab() function from package AICcmodavg to calculate AIC on the list of models you have created and do the comparison. The code will produce the following output table. A quick look at the AIC scores reveal that model m7 is considered best for this data. Model m7 included elevation and forest cover as predictor of abundance.

library(AICcmodavg)
fit.list <- aictab(c(m1, m2, m3, m4, m5, m6, m7, m8, m9, m10, m11, m12, m13, m14))
fit.list

Making predictions

Probably the best part of modeling is that the model can be used to predict expected abundance and detection when given new data. Now what you want to do is the inference and prediction part. Now that you have identified the top model (model that receives more support than the rest of the models), you want to understand what the model is telling you.

Single point

For example, you could ask what is the average abundance of a sampling site if sampling is situated at 1500m above sea level and has 40% forest cover? For predicting a single data point, you can also use the plogis() function to calculate probability, like the example shown below. Since model m7 has covariates, you need to factor in the covariate effect and the value of interest in your calculation.

#what is the expected abundance of a sampling site if it was located at 1500m?
predict.abundance <- exp(m7@opt$par[1] + m7@opt$par[2]*1500 + m7@opt$par[3]*40)
predict.abundance 
## [1] 1.188447

2D surface

You can also illustrate by plotting the prediction of abundance over the range of covariate values observed. To predict a range of data points, you will need to use the predict() function instead. The predict() function returns the predictions with standard errors and confidence intervals. This information can be used to create plots.

##load graphics packages 
library(ggplot2)
library(cowplot)

##predict abundance across elevation range
#prepare new data
pred.elev <- data.frame(
    elevation = seq(min(umf@siteCovs$elevation, na.rm = TRUE),  # min elevation cover
                    max(umf@siteCovs$elevation, na.rm = TRUE),  # max elevation cover
                    length = 100),                              # number of points in range
    forest = rep(mean(umf@siteCovs$forest), length = 100))      # average forest cover 
#predict abundance with new data
pred.elevation <- predict(
    m7,                         # model to predict from
    type = "state",             # sub model to predict from
    newdata = pred.elev,        # new values to use for predictions
    append = TRUE)              # add newdata to prediction data frame
#setup elevation plot
gpred.elevation <- ggplot() +
    geom_line(aes(x = pred.elevation$elevation, y = pred.elevation$Predicted),
              color = "blue", size = 1) +
    geom_ribbon(aes(x = pred.elevation$elevation, ymin = pred.elevation$lower,
                ymax = pred.elevation$upper), fill = "skyblue", alpha = 0.1) +
    ylab("Average abundance") +
    xlab("Elevation (m)") + 
    ylim(0, 10) +    
    theme_light()
   
##predict abundance across forest cover range
#prepare new data
pred.fore <- data.frame(
    elevation = rep(mean(umf@siteCovs$elevation), length = 100),    # average elevation
    forest = seq(min(umf@siteCovs$forest, na.rm = TRUE),            # min forest cover
                    max(umf@siteCovs$forest, na.rm = TRUE),         # max forest cover
                    length = 100))                                  # number of points in range
#predict count with new data
pred.forest <- predict(
    m7,                         # model to predict from
    type = "state",             # sub model to predict from
    newdata = pred.fore,        # new values to use for predictions
    append = TRUE)              # add newdata to prediction data frame
#setup elevation plot
gpred.forest <- ggplot() +
    geom_line(aes(x = pred.forest$forest, y = pred.forest$Predicted),
              color = "dark green", size = 1) +
    geom_ribbon(aes(x = pred.forest$forest, ymin = pred.forest$lower,
                ymax = pred.forest$upper), fill = "light green", alpha = 0.1) +
    ylab("Average abundance") +
    xlab("Forest cover (%)") + 
    ylim(0, 10) +    
    theme_light()

#plot detection predictions side-by-side    
plot_grid(gpred.elevation, gpred.forest, nrow = 1)

3D surface

You can also illustrate by mapping the predictions of abundance. For prediction over a surface, you will need spatial forest cover data of the whole FMU. You can get such data through websites such as the Global Forest Watch and the USGS, although you may need to do some fiddling before the data can be used for analysis. Now load in the data you want to predict abundance for. This data needs to have two columns for longitude and latitude values for each site/pixel and a column for the covariate value (each row is one site/pixel).

sector <- read.csv("sector.csv", header = TRUE)
siteCovs.map <- data.frame(elevation = sector$elevation,
                           forest = sector$forest)
head(siteCovs.map)
##   elevation forest
## 1       340      6
## 2       340     11
## 3       380      4
## 4       390     72
## 5       357      9
## 6       357      5

Just like before, you will need to use the predict() function to estimate abundance, standard errors, and confidence intervals for each site/pixel.

predict.abundance <- predict(
    m7,                             # model to predict from 
    type = "state",                 # sub model to predict from
    newdata = siteCovs.map,         # new values to use for predictions
    append = TRUE)                  # add newdata to prediction data frame
#save predictions
save(predict.abundance, file = "predict.abundance.RData")
